<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n58061e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n58" href="#n58061e">N58 (VI.B.30)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n58all.htm#n58061e"> 61(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to be = to have / = snatch from / moon</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is in reality no such verb as a pure copula, no such original conception, our very word exist means &ldquo;to stand forth,&rdquo; to show oneself by a definite act. &ldquo;Is&rdquo; comes from the Aryan root as, to breathe. &ldquo;Be&rdquo; is from <i>bhu</i> to grow. <p>In Chinese the chief verb for <mark>&ldquo;is&rdquo; not only means actively &ldquo;to have,&rdquo;</mark> but shows by its derivation that it expresses something even more concrete, namely, <mark>&ldquo;to snatch from the moon with the hand.&rdquo;</mark> Here the baldest symbol of prosaic analysis is transformed by magic into a splendid flash of concrete poetry.</p> <small> Ernest Fenollosa, &ldquo;The Chinese Written Character as a Medium for Poetry&rdquo;, in <a name="EFCW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EFCW"><cite title="source">Instigations of Ezra Pound</cite></a> (1920) 369f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
